</ul>
<hr />
<dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
  <a name="crookedcross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROOKED CROSS</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swastika">swastika</a>&rsquo;.
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d1876.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1876.gif" alt="crooked cross" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of the <a href="de}ns_hj.html">Hitler Youth</a> 1933 &ndash; 1945, Germany (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="cross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS </dt>
  <dd>1) Two stripes or bands of equal width (and in the same colour) but of unequal 
  length, that extend to the outer edges of the flag, canton or panel they 
  occupy, and intersect at right angles in the exact centre of that flag, canton 
  or panel &ndash; a St George-type cross, a cross fixed, cross throughout, an upright centred, 
  centred, regular or (inaccurately) a square cross � see �<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#squarecross">square cross 1)</a>� (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-s.html#stgeorge">St George&rsquo;s Cross</a>&rsquo;).
  </dd>
  <dd>2) A charge, which may or may not reach the outer edges of the shield, flag, canton 
  or panel it occupies, and which may not have straight edges but which has four segments 
  meeting at right angles at a central point &ndash; but see note below. 
  </dd>
  <dd>3) A generic name for two stripes of the same colour (although two/three 
  colour variants exist see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#crosscounterchanged">cross counterchanged</a>&rsquo; 
  plus &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcr.html#crossgyronny">cross gyronny</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#tripartite">tripartite</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#layeredcross">layered cross</a>&rsquo;) and any width, crossing 
  the field of a flag, panel or canton in any manner (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs0.html#saltire">saltire</a>&rsquo;
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs1.html#scandinaviancross">Scandinavian cross</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4091.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4091.gif" alt="[cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4092.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4092.gif" alt="[cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d104b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d104b.gif" alt="[Pisa, Italy]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4093.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4093.gif" alt="[cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="fr-savoy.html">Savoy</a>, France (fotw); 
  National Flag of <a href="ch.html">Switzerland</a> (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="it-pisa.html">Pisa</a>, Italy (fotw);
  State Flag/Naval Ensign of <a href="dk_state.html">Denmark</a> (fotw).</em>
  </p>
	<p>
    <em>Please note however, that whilst 
  several of the types 
  used on flags are detailed separately herein &ndash; the cross throughout as given in 
  1) above, </em> <a href="vxt-dvg4.html#greekcross"><em>the Greek cross</em></a><em>, the 
    </em> 
  <a href="vxt-dvc2.html#celticcross"><em>Celtic cross</em></a><em>, the 
  </em> 
  <a href="vxt-dvs1.html#scandinaviancross"><em>Scandinavian cross</em></a><em>, the 
    </em> 
  <a href="vxt-dvs0.html#saltire"><em>saltire</em></a><em> (or diagonal cross), 
    </em> 
  <a href="vxt-dvcs.html#crosslorraine"><em>Cross of Lorraine</em></a><em>, 
  the </em> <a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swastika"><em>swastika</em></a><em>, 
  and the </em> <a href="vxt-dv-m.html#maltesecross"><em>Maltese cross</em></a><em> &ndash; numerous other 
  variants exist (mostly used in heraldry but which also sometimes appear on flags), 
  and the majority of these are listed below.</em></p>
  </dd>

  <hr/><a name="crossanchory"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS ANCHORY</dt>
  <dd>An alternative heraldic term for a cross moline - see  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcr.html#crossmoline">cross moline</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  &nbsp;<a href="../images/v/vxt-d3469.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d3469.gif" alt="cross anchory example" border="0" height="108" /></a><br/>
  <em>Flag of <a href="be-vbrwo.html">Wezembeek-Oppem</a>, Belgium (fotw)</em>

  <hr/><a name="crossannuletty"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS ANNULETTY</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term covering a sun cross - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs8.html#suncross">sun cross</a>&rsquo; and its following note.
  <p>
  &nbsp;<a href="../images/v/vxt-d3428.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d3428.gif" alt="cross annuletty example" border="0" height="108" /></a><br/>
  <em>Flag of <a href="de-hv-bd.html#oz">Otze</a>, Germany (fotw)</em>

  <hr /><a name="crossbar"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS BAR (CROSS-BAR or CROSSBAR) </dt>
  <dd>The transverse rod, from which a flag is suspended, either attached in the centre or 
  from one end, or hung by cords from a vertical pole or poles (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvba.html">banner 2)</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvba.html">banner 3)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#frame">frame 1)</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#frame">frame 2)</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#framedflag">framed flag</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg2.html#gonfalon">gonfalon</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvv2.html#vexillum">vexillum</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2818.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2818.gif" alt="cross bar example" border="0" height="242" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2834.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2834.gif" alt="cross bar example" border="0" height="216" /></a>
  <br>
  <em><a href="it-bg003.html">Gonfalon of Albano Sant'Alessandro</a>, Italy (fotw); Gonfalon of 
  <a href="it-or010.html">Baradili</a>, Italy (fotw)  </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="crossbarbed"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS BARBED</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for an arrow cross - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva7.html#arrowcross">arrow cross</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2093.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2093.gif" alt="Arrow Cross flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br/>
  <em>Former Flag of the  
  <a href="ve}1.html#falven">Falange Venezolana</a>, Venezuela (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="crossbotonny"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS BOTONNY (BOTTONNY or BOTTON&Eacute;E)</dt>
  <dd>The alternative heraldic terms for a cross that does not usually extend to the edges of a shield, flag, canton or panel, but whose ends 
  each are formed by three discs � a trefoil or treflee 
  cross (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 2)</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd3.html#disc">disc</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt2.html#trefoil">trefoil</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1898.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1898.gif" alt="cross botonny" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d691.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d691.gif" alt="botonny cross example" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4346.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d4346.gif" alt="Vestby" border="0" height="108" /></a><br/>
  <em>Flag of the <a href="no_chno.html">Church of Norway</a> (fotw); Arms of <a href="hr-vu-ne.html">Negoslavci</a>, 
  Croatia (fotw); Flag of <a href="no-02-11.html">Vestby</a>, Norway (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

<hr /><a name="cross-cantonee"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS-CANTON&Eacute;E (or CANTONED)</dt>
  <dd>The alternative heraldic terms for a cross which may or may not extend to the edges of a shield, flag, canton or panel, but which has four further crosses (or other charges) arranged around it � a cross cantoned (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc1.html#canton">canton 3)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc1.html#cantoned">cantoned 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvct.html#crosspattee">cross patt&#233;e</a>&rsquo;, and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvct.html#crosspotent">cross potent</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvct.html#crosspotentcantonee">cross potent canton&#233;e&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d701d.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d701d.gif" alt="example" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3131.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3131.gif" alt="national flag of Georgia" border="0" width="162" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3132.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3132.gif" alt="national flag of Georgia" border="0" width="108" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Example; 
  Flag of <a href="ge-tian.html">Tianeti</a>, Georgia (fotw); 
  Arms of The <a href="rel-c-kj.html">Kingdom of Jerusalem</a> c1200 (CS)
  <p>
  Please note as may be seen in the illustrations above, various types of cross can be used to make up a cross canton&#233;e, and that a Jerusalem Cross (a cross-potent canton&#233;e constructed of a cross-potent and four Greek crosses or of five crosses-potent) is one specific type. </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="crossceltic"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS-CELTIC</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for a Celtic cross - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#celticcross">Celtic cross</a>&rsquo;
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d690a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d690a.gif" alt="Celtic cross" border="0" width="162" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3047a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3047a.gif" alt="Celtic cross" border="0" width="107" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag and Logo of the  
  <a href="gb-wa-ch.html">Church 
  in Wales</a>, UK (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr/><a name="crossclechee"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS-CLECH&Eacute;E</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for a cross that does not generally extend to the edges of a shield, flag, panel or flag, but whose arms are in the form of (usually irregular) lozenges or fusils � a cross-lozengy or cross-fusilly (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 
  2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  �<a href="vxt-dvcs.html#crossofpisa">cross of Pisa</a>�, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#fusil">fusil</a>&rsquo;, �<a href="vxt-dvl4.html#lozenge">lozenge</a>&rsquo; 
  and �<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#occitancross">occitan cross</a>&rsquo;).  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3429a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3429a.gif" alt="arms - Mogilany, Poland" border="0" width="88" height="105" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3429.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3429.gif" alt="flag - Mogilany, Poland" border="0" width="175" height="105" /></a><br />
  <em>Arms and Flag of 
  <a href="de-pe_ww.html">Woltwiesche</a>, Germany (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr/><a name="crosscounterchanged"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS-COUNTERCHANGED</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for a cross that generally extends to the edges of a shield, panel, banner of arms or flag, and which is divided along its horizontal and vertical centre-line with the tinctures of the field and cross usually (but not exclusively) alternating in adjacent quarters � a counterchanged cross or cross counter-quartered � but compare with 
  &lsquo;cross gyronny&rsquo; (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvco.html#counterchanged">counterchanged</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#dominicancross">Dominican cross</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-q.html#quarter">quarter 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#tincture">tincture</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1831a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1831a.gif" alt="[cross-counterchanged]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4524.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4524.gif" alt="[cross-counterchanged]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1832.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1832.gif" alt="[cross-counterchanged]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="hr-zg-za.html">Zapre�i&#263;</a>, Croatia (fotw); 
  Flag of 
  <a href="ch-gr-da.html">Kreis Davos</a>, Switzerland (fotw)
  <p>
  Please note that a cross that is divided only along either its horizontal or vertical centre-line is properly blazoned using a full description � for example, �party per fess argent and azure a cross-humetty 
  counterchanged&quot; as shown below.</em>
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3136.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3136.gif" alt="[cross-counterchanged]" border="0" height="108" /></a> <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="mt-67.html">Zurrieq</a>, Malta (fotw)</em><hr/><a name="crosscounterquartered"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS COUNTER-QUARTERED</dt>
  <dd>1) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#crosscounterchanged">cross counterchanged</a>&rsquo;.<br>
  2) The term that may also be used when the centre of a cross of this general type is obscured as illustrated below - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcr.html#crossgyronny">cross gyronny</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1877b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1877b.gif" alt="[cross-counterquartered]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1877a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1877a.gif" alt="[cross-counterquartered]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3134.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3134.gif" alt="[cross-counterquartered]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br>
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="cz-pz-tk.html">Tursko</a>, Czechia (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="es-se-pr.html">Palomares del R�o</a>, Spain (fotw)</em><hr /><a name="cross-couped"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS-COUPED </dt>
  <dd>A heraldic term sometimes used when a cross (either plain or decorated) does not extend to edges of a shield, banner of arms or flag (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvco.html#couped">couped 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg4.html#greekcross">Greek cross</a>&rsquo;).  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4309.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4449.gif" alt="cross of eight points" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1878.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1878.gif" alt="cross couped" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d104b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d104b.gif" alt="[Pisa, Italy]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="ru-ud-mz.html">Mozhginsky District</a>, Russia  
  (fotw); National Flag of <a href="to.html">Tonga</a> (fotw); Flag of <a href="it-pisa.html">Pisa</a>, 
  Italy (fotw)<p>
  Please note that, unless referring to a plain cross, this term is always accompanied by a further description, for example a �Cross 
  of Pisa couped� 
  as illustrated above, or a �<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#crosscrosslet">cross crosslet</a> couped� as shown in the following definition.</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="crosscrosslet"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS CROSSLET</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for a cross which does not usually extend to the edges of a shield, flag canton or panel, but whose arms have a short transverse bar inserted (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 2)</a>&rsquo;).   <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2497.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2497.gif" alt="botonny cross" border="0" height="108"  /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4901.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4901.gif" alt="botonny cross" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4347.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4347.gif" alt="botonny cross" border="0" height="108"  /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="pl-wp-db.html">Dobrzyca</a>, Poland (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="md-costu.html">Costuleni</a>, Moldova (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="nl-li-ec.html#ec">Echt</a>, The Netherlands (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="crossengrailed"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS ENGRAILED</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve1.html#engrailed">engrailed</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1340a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1340a.gif" alt="cross engrailed" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1340b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1340b.gif" alt="cross engrailed" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Arms and Flag of <a href="pt-mrtes.html">Espinho</a>, Portugal (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="crossequipolle"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CROSS EQUIPOLL&Eacute; (or EQUIPOLL&Eacute;E)</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve4.html#equipolle">equipoll&eacute;</a>&rsquo;.
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d1014a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1014a.gif" alt="S&#233;, Portugal" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1014b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1014b.gif" alt="S&#233;, Portugal" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Arms and Flag of <a href="pt-funse.html">S&#233;</a>, Portugal (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

